text: Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology https://doi.org/10.1007/s00210-020-02043-5 Inhibitory and ameliorative effect of heliomycin derived from actinomycete on induced hepatocellular carcinoma in rats Ahmed S. Alazzouni 1 & Abdulla A. Mahmoud 2 & Mohamed M. Omran 2 & Ehab A. Essawy 2 & Mohga S. Abdalla 2 & Mohamed S. Abdelfattah 2,3 Received: 22 September 2020 / Accepted: 13 December 2020 # The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer-Verlag GmbH, DE part of Springer Nature 2021

Abstract The hepatoprotective activity of heliomycin obtained from the culture broth of actinomycete AB5 against diethylnitrosamine (DEN)-induced hepatic cancer in Wistar rats was estimated. Heliomycin exhibited a significant decrease in the levels of alanine transaminase (ALT), aspartate transaminase (AST), and alkaline phosphatase (ALP) compared to the positive control. For instance, the heliomycin group after 20 weeks showed a significant decline in ALT, AST, and ALP values (70.75 ± 5.12, 140.25 ± 11.75, and 163.25 ± 18.66, respectively) compared to the positive control group (170.00 ± 9.55, 252.75 ± 12.33, and 278.00 ± 21.32, respectively). Additionally, the isolated compound showed a highly significant decrease in serum alpha- fetoprotein (AFP) levels. After 8, 16, and 20 weeks, the mean values of AFP in the heliomycin group revealed a highly significant decrease (33.62 ± 2.46, 30.00 ± 4.05, and 28.50 ± 2.64, respectively) compared to the positive control group (49.45 ± 3.03, 81.90 ± 6.70, and 90.75 ± 5.12, respectively). The histopathological investigation of liver sections supported the results of biochemical analysis. It was demonstrated that heliomycin showed histological improvement of hepatocytes and marked increase of nuclear pyknotic with clear cytoplasm, which is a sign of improving the apoptotic pathway of malignant cells. It also displayed marked fibrosis at most of the malignant cells and the development of some regenerative nodules. Heliomycin showed moderate immunoreactivity with alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), and proliferation cell nuclear antigen (PCNA) compared to the positive control group. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first study to report the anticancer activity of heliomycin against hepatocellular carcinoma in vivo. Keywords Hepatocellular carcinoma . Heliomycin . Liver enzymes . Histopathology . Immunohistochemistry

Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is one of the most common aggressive cancers and causes death worldwide (Ghouri et al. 2017; Bray et al. 2018; Rawla et al. 2018; Yang et al. 2019). This type of cancer occurs in patients with chronic liver 2 Chemistry Department, Faculty of Science, Helwan University, 3 Natural Products Research Unit, Chemistry Department, Faculty of Zoology Department, Faculty of Science, Helwan University, Cairo 11795, Egypt Science, Helwan University, Cairo 11795, Egypt mohga.shafiek@science.helwan.edu.eg mabdelfattah@science.helwan.edu.eg disease such as cirrhosis produced by hepatitis B and C (Kohli 2016). Additionally, exposure to mycotoxins like afla- toxin B1 is considered a risk factor for HCC (Wild and Gong 2009). By looking at the cancer maps, we find that hepatocel- lular carcinoma (HCC) is known in many diverse areas in Africa and Asia (Ashtari et al. 2015). In Egypt, HCC is the most cause of cancer death in males and represented a signif- icant public health problem (Bray et al. 2018; Rashed et al. 2020). It was reported that the leading choice for the treatment of cancer is chemotherapy, but it causes damage to tissues and healthy cells (Raguz and Yagüe 2008). Natural products are bioorganic molecules produced by different living organisms, which usually possess some phar- macological activities (Dias et al. 2012; Badr et al. 2014; Ramana et al. 2014). They can modulate human cancers (Ko and Auyeung 2012) and reduce chemotherapy’s side effects (Chen et al. 2010). As per the literature, microorganisms are an essential source of bioactive natural compounds with

unique carbon skeletons (Abdelfattah and Rohr 2006; Abdelfattah et al. 2011; Blunt et al. 2012; Citron et al. 2012; Subramani and Sipkema 2019). Most of the main therapeutic agents used for chemotherapy are natural products or their semisynthetic analogs, mainly formed by microorganisms. In particular, actinomycetes are Gram-positive, aerobic, my- celial bacteria, and their DNA riches with high G+C nucleo- tide content (> 55%) (Barka et al. 2016). Actinobacteria are the manufacturers of a considerable number of secondary me- tabolites with anticancer activity. These metabolites belong to different categories of compounds such as peptides, macrolides indolocarbazoles, and anthracyclines. Heliomycin is a rare aromatic polyketide isolated for the first time from Streptomyces resistomycificus (Brockmann and Schmidt-Kastner 1951). It has diverse biological activities such as anticancer, antibacterial, and antiviral activities (Shiono et al. 2002; Podol’ skaya et al. 2005; Adinarayana et al. 2006; Vijayabharathi et al. 2011). Additionally, it in- hibits the RNA polymerase, protein synthesis, and histone deacetylase enzymes (Haupt et al. 1975; Abdelfattah et al. 2018). To the best of our knowledge, there are no available data about heliomycin’s effect on hepatocellular carcinoma in vivo. Therefore, the present study aims to explore heliomycin’s ability to inhibit and ameliorate the effects of diethylnitrosamine (DEN)-induced hepatic cancer in Wistar rats. In this research work, plasma liver enzymes such as ALT, AST, and ALP and tumor marker plasma alpha- fetoprotein were evaluated. Histopathological examination and immunohistochemistry of liver tissues were also per- formed. This current study leads to the discovery of heliomycin as a natural therapeutic compound that may be used to treat hepatocellular carcinoma. Production and identification of heliomycin

Well-grown agar plates of the actinobacteria AB5 were used to inoculate 60 of 250 cm3 Erlenmeyer flasks, each containing 100 mL of Waksman media (Mahmoud et al. 2019). The flasks were incubated at 35 ± 1 °C for 4 days on a rotary shaker (150 rpm). After 4 days, the flasks were harvested and centrifuged at 4000 rpm for 10 min. The resulting myce- lial cake was extracted three times with methanol, while the water phase was extracted three times with ethyl acetate. Both extracts were combined and evaporated under a vacuum. The extract was dissolved in methanol and left overnight to get a yellow precipitate, filtrated, and washed multiple times with methanol to give 1.90 g of heliomycin. The chemical structure of the produced compound was identified by NMR and MS spectroscopy (Abdelfattah et al. 2018). Spectroscopic data of heliomycin The spectroscopic data of heliomycin is as follows: orange solid; (-)-ESI-MS: m/z (%) = 375 ([M-H]−; 100); 1HNMR ([D6] DMSO, 400 MHz): δH = 14.28 (s, 1H, 7-OH), 14.23 (s, 1H, 3-OH), 13.78 (s, 1H, 5-OH), 11.76 (br. s, 1H, 10- OH), 7.15 (s, 1H, 11-H), 6.76 (s, 1H, 8-H), 6.19 (s, 1H, 4- H), 2.79 (s, 3H, 9-CH3), 1.82 (s, 6H, 1-CH3). Hepatocarcinogenesis model

Male Wistar rats between 15 and 20 weeks of age and weighing 150 ~ 170 g were obtained from the El-Masry Center at Faculty of Medicine, Ain Shams University. The animals were housed in polypropylene cages at 25 ± 1 °C, with a relative humidity of 55 ± 5% and 12 h light/dark. The rats were fed a standard diet, and water was obtainable ad libitum. All the animals were adapted to the environmental conditions for 1 week before the beginning of experiments. Determination of LD50 of heliomycin Estimation of LD50 is a common primary step in the evalua- tion of the toxic character of a compound. It was determined for heliomycin using the up-and-down procedure (Bruce 1985). The LD50 of heliomycin was 25 mg/kg, and the rec- ommended injected dose was 2.5 mg/kg. The experimental hepatocarcinogenesis model was initiat- ed by diethylnitrosamine (DEN) (Sigma Chemical Co., USA). A total of seventy Wistar rats were used and classi- fied into two major groups (Table 1). Group I rats (10 rats) were left as a negative control and received normal saline by oral administration during the induction period. The main group II (60 rats) were treated orally DEN with a dose of 20 mg/kg five times per week for 6 weeks (total of 30 doses equivalent to 600 mg/kg) (Darwish and El- Boghdady 2013). The rats of group II were divided into three subgroups (IIa, IIb, and IIc) of twenty animals each. Group IIa was a positive control (HCC-induced). The rats of group IIb were treated with cisplatin as a commercial drug (HCC-induced + cisplatin ) with a dose of 1 mg/kg three times per week with a total accumulative dose of 24 mg/kg (Wang et al. 2003). Group IIc represented the rats treated with heliomycin (HCC-induced + heliomycin) with a dose of 2.5 mg/kg three times per week. Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Arch Pharmacol

Blood samples were collected by the end of each time interval according to the procedure of Thavasu et al. (1992). Concerning liver sampling, specimens were ex- cised rapidly and washed with isotonic saline. The liver was fixed in formalin (10%) for more than 48 h for histological examination and immunohistochemical study. Measurement of liver enzymes Serum of each animal in all groups was subjected to serum alanine transaminase (ALT), aspartate transaminase (AST), and alkaline phosphatase (ALP) analysis. The ALT and AST activity level was deter- mined by kinetic UV-optimized methods (Bergmeyer et al. 1986a, b). Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) was performed using the standard colorimetric technique with the Randox assay kit (Rec 1972). Estimation of alpha-fetoprotein The serum alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) level was estimated by using a rat alpha-fetoprotein ELISA kit (NBP2-66656). The kit was purchased from Novus Biologicals, USA and used according to the manufac- turer’s instructions. Tissue processing for histopathological examination The tis- sues were prepared and stained by hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stains (Alturkistani et al. 2015). Immunohistopathology Immunoperoxidase staining of prolif- eration cell nuclear antigen (PCNA) was achieved using PCNA polyclonal antibody (Thermo Fisher Scientific, TX, USA). Staining of the caspase-3 was performed according to the manufacturer’s protocol of Biocare Medical (Walnut Creek, CA). Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) was stained using the protocol of Abcam (UK). Isolation and structure elucidation of heliomycin During our screening program for bioactive secondary metab- olites from bacteria, heliomycin was isolated from actinomy- cete AB5 (Abdelfattah et al. 2016b, 2018; Elmallah et al. 2017; Mahmoud et al. 2019). The strain was optimized to produce 320 mg/L of heliomycin in Waksman media at 35 °C for 96 h. The molecular weight was estimated to be 376 Da based on the ESI-MS (m/z 375 [M - H]−) in the negative ion mode, as shown in S1 Fig. The 1H-NMR spectrum (S2 Fig) of the isolated compound revealed four hydroxyl groups (δH = 14.55, 14.36, 14.07, and 11.40), three aromatic protons ap- peared as singlets (δH = 7.21, 7.01, and 6.31), one methyl group (δH = 2.90), and two magnetically equivalent methyl groups (δH = 1.56). The isolated compound was identified as heliomycin (Fig. 1) by comparing these spectral data with the literature (Kock et al. 2005). Effect of heliomycin on alpha-fetoprotein

The mean levels of AFP in serum at different treatment times are shown in Table 3 and ST3. After 8, 16, and 20 weeks of treatments, the mean values of AFP in the posi- tive control group increase significantly (p ˂ 0.001) com- pared to the negative control group. In the heliomycin- treated group, the AFP showed a highly significant de- crease (p ˂ 0.001) compared to the positive control group. After 8 weeks of treatment, the mean AFP values also showed a highly significant decrease (p ˂ 0.001) compared to the positive control group. Typical hepatocytes arranged in usual hepatic cords and normal liver sinusoids were also observed (Fig. 2).

In contrast, the sections of the liver of the positive con- trol group after 8 weeks showed undifferentiated hepato- cellular carcinoma with the presence of malignant cells (MC), inflammatory cells (INFC), and congested central vein (CV) with mucinous secretion (Fig. 3a). Nodular structure with large cells (LC), prominent neovasculariza- tion (PNV), bile canaliculi (BC) with ballooning hepato- cytes, and clear cells were observed (Fig. 3b). The positive control group also revealed thickened liver cell plates and thick trabecula (Fig. 3c). Additionally, it showed nodular well-differentiated HCC with large cells (LC) and undif- ferentiated HCC with small cell changes (SCC) (Fig. 3d). After 16 weeks, the liver sections displayed marked devel- opmental changes of malignant tissue rosette shape around congested CV (Fig. 3e). It also exhibited active undiffer- entiated cells in nodular structure with large cells and an inverted N/C ratio (Fig. 3f). The development of a new malignant intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma with irregular cuboidal cells surrounded by sclerotic area was observed (Fig. 3g-h). After 20 weeks, the liver sections exhibited congested CV with prominent vascularization (PV) (Fig. 3i). It also revealed marked infiltration of inflammatory cells (INFC) and bile canaliculi (BC) with obvious devel- opment of cholangiocarcinoma with glandular epithelium (GE) (Fig. 3j-l). drugs are drug resistance and the dangerous side effects of chemotherapy. Therefore, it is essential to detect the effect of promising natural products that have anticancer activity in vivo (Karpiński and Adamczak 2018). Among them, sec- ondary metabolites extracted from actinomycetes that are used as anticancer agents (Takahashi and Omura 2003; Chakraborty et al. 2007; Abdelfattah et al. 2016a). As per the literature, heliomycin had potent cytotoxic activity against the hepatic carcinoma cell line (HepG2) (Vijayabharathi et al. 2011; Elmallah et al. 2020). For studying the effect of heliomycin on hepatocarcinogenesis, diethylnitrosamine (DEN) has been used for chemical induction of liver cancer in rats (Chakraborty et al. 2007). Males of Wistar rats were Fig. 5 Immunohistochemistry staining of AFP for different animal groups after 8, 16, and 20 weeks of treatments. a-d Stained after 8 weeks. a Negative control group. b Positive control group. c Cisplatin- treated group. d Heliomycin-treated group. e and f Stained after 16 weeks. intraperitoneally injected with cisplatin and heliomycin. The animals were sacrificed after 8, 16, and 20 weeks from the beginning of the experiment and the following parameters were estimated in plasma: alanine aminotransferase (ALT), aspartate aminotransferase (AST), alkaline phosphatase (ALP), and alpha-fetoprotein (AFP). Additionally, immuno- histochemical staining for alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), caspase-3, and proliferation cell nuclear antigen (PCNA) was carried out in the liver tissue.

Our results illustrated that the mean level of liver enzymes in the positive control group is highly significantly increased (p ˂ 0.001) compared to the negative control group. It was reported that serum ALT, AST, and ALP activities had been significantly increased in the positive group of rats that re- ceived DEN compared to the negative group (Jahan et al. 2011; Dai et al. 2013; Kumar et al. 2014; Gnanaraja and Prakash 2014). Heliomycin exhibited a significant decrease in the mean levels of ALT, AST, and ALP compared to the positive control group (Table 2). It also showed improvement in the hepatocytes compared to the HCC-induced group and cisplatin-treated group. On the other hand, the cisplatin- treated group died after 8 weeks and exhibited a highly sig- nificant increase in the mean level of ALT, AST, and ALP activity (Table 2) compared to the negative group. This e Positive control group. f Heliomycin-treated group. g and h Stained after 20 weeks. g Positive control group. h Heliomycin-treated group (original magnification × 400)

elevation in serum liver enzymes indicated damage and tox- icity in the liver (Nyblom et al. 2004). The serum alpha- fetoprotein (AFP) was used as a diagnostic tool and consid- ered a specific HCC marker (Sell 2008). Our data illustrated that the mean level of serum AFP in the positive control group showed a highly significant increase (p ˂ 0.001) compared to the negative control group (Table 3). It was reported that the AFP level showed a significant increase in serum of DEN- treated rats (Sell et al. 1983; Liu et al. 2012; Song et al. 2013; Perumal et al. 2018). The heliomycin-treated group displayed a highly significant decrease (p ˂ 0.001) in the mean value of AFP compared to the positive control group after 8, 16, and 20 weeks of treatment. The possible explanation for this amelio- rative effect may be the induction of apoptosis, inhibition of proteins, and RNA synthesis. It was reported that anthracimycin from marine actinobacteria induced apoptosis and terminated cell proliferation in human HCC cell lines (Hayashi et al. 2017). Other criteria of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) can be expressed in the histopathological pattern trabecula (macro- and microtrabecula), neovascularization, and absence of por- tal tract in the tumor (Schlageter et al. 2014). As shown in Fig. 3, there are no portal tracts observed within the tumor, and all the classical histologic patterns (i.e., trabecular/sinusoidal, Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Arch Pharmacol Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Arch Pharmacol Fig. 6 Immunohistochemistry staining of caspase-3 for different animal groups after 8, 16, and 20 weeks of treatments. a-d Stained after 8 weeks. a Negative control group. b Positive control group. c Cisplatin-treated group. d Heliomycin-treated group. e and f Stained after 16 weeks. e

pseudoglandular, solid, and undifferentiated) are present. Treatment of animals with cisplatin (S3 Fig) showed improve- ment in hepatocytes’ histological structure (Guicciardi and Gores 2009). Cure of HCC with heliomycin showed some histological improvement of hepatocytes and marked increase of pyknotic nuclei with clear cytoplasm. These results reflected liver cirrhosis and fibrosis (Fig. 4i-l). Additionally, a marked pyknotic change, fibrosis at most malignant cells, and HCC nodules were observed (Fig. 4i-j). The development of some regenerative nodules, a dysplastic change of liver tissue, was also detected (Fig. 4k-l). Immunohistochemical study of the negative and the posi- tive control groups showed a negative and extensive immu- noreactivity in the alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) serum level at dif- ferent times of the experiment (Fig. 5). The heliomycin-treated group showed moderate immunoreactivity after 8 weeks. After 16 and 20 weeks, the heliomycin group displayed a marked reduction in the AFP level compared to the positive control group. These results can be explained by the inhibition of cellular proliferation and enhancement of the apoptotic ac- tivity of HCC cells. After 16 and 20 weeks, the heliomycin- treated group has increased immunoreactivity, which may be due to the dysplastic changes and formation of a regenerative Positive control group. f Heliomycin-treated group. g and h Stained after 20 weeks. g Positive control group. h Heliomycin-treated group (original magnification × 400)

nodule. Our result also showed a marked increase in caspase-3 immunoreaction in all stages of heliomycin treatments (Fig. 6). After 8 weeks, severe immunoreaction occurred for the groups treated with cisplatin (Fig. 6c) and heliomycin (Fig. 6d). After 16 and 20 weeks, caspase-3 showed a severe reac- tion with heliomycin-treated groups, which can be explained by enhancing the apoptotic pathway of malignant cells by heliomycin. In the case of PCNA immunoreactivity, the pos- itive control group showed an extensive reaction, where the number of positive nuclei is directly related to the severity and grading of HCC. As shown in Fig. 7, the number of positive nuclei in the positive control group is greater than the number in the treated group with heliomycin. It was reported that in the HCC, PCNA is overexpressed and functioning in both DNA duplication and DNA repair (Venturi et al. 2008). We conclude that heliomycin has inhibitory and amelioration effects against HCC-induced animal models with less toxicity, side effects, and increased survival rate than traditional che- motherapeutic drugs like cisplatin. The use of heliomycin in Fig. 7 Immunohistochemistry staining of PCNA for different animal groups after 8, 16, and 20 weeks of treatments. a-d Stained after 8 weeks. a Negative control group. b Positive control group. c Cisplatin- treated group. d Heliomycin-treated group. e and f Stained after 16 weeks. the treatment of HCC enhances the apoptotic activity and tissue repair, and prevents the development of another malig- nant disease. Our study may introduce heliomycin as a useful drug candidate for treating hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). This compound should be investigated on the level of the molecular mechanism of HCC development. Heliomycin mode of action against malignant and tumor cells to treat other malignancy types ought to be evaluated. Additionally, a com- bination of heliomycin with radiotherapy may be considered in future hepatocellular carcinoma studies.
